# Testing

Coding patterns for writing and organizing tests. IF your project has tests, follow these patterns. Start with critical paths and expand coverage over time.

> All numeric values (thresholds, sizes, timings, percentages) in this file are `[DEFAULT]` - adjust per project.

---

## Testing Pyramid

```
         /  E2E  \          <- Few: critical user flows only
        /----------\
       / Integration \      <- Moderate: API endpoints, service interactions
      /----------------\
     /    Unit Tests     \  <- Many: pure functions, utilities, business logic
    /____________________\
```

- **Unit tests**: Fast, isolated, test one function/method. Mock external dependencies.
- **Integration tests**: Test multiple units working together. Real database (test instance), real HTTP calls to your server.
- **E2E tests**: Test full user flows through the actual UI. Slowest, most brittle, most valuable for critical paths.

---

## When to add tests (agents)

| Situation | Policy |
|-----------|--------|
| Project has test harness | **SHOULD** add/update tests on behavior changes |
| No test harness | **Do not** add tests unless the user asks |
| Every change | **Consider** whether a test is warranted - use judgment (including CSS-only: manual verify may suffice) |

---

## What to Test

### ALWAYS Test

**Principle:** Test behavior that would cause user-visible bugs, security holes, or data corruption if broken.

[REFERENCE] Scenarios that almost always warrant tests:

- Authentication flows (if your app has auth: session creation, expiry, invalidation)
- Permission checks (authorized vs. unauthorized access)
- Input validation (valid, invalid, edge cases, empty, too long)
- CRUD operations (prioritize by risk - critical entities first, not exhaustive coverage of every entity)
- Business logic (calculations, state transitions, conditional behavior)
- Error handling (network failure, invalid data, missing resources)
- Edge cases (empty lists, max values, concurrent operations)

### NEVER Test

**Principle:** Don't test implementation details or things the framework already guarantees.

[REFERENCE] Common testing anti-patterns:

- Framework internals (React rendering, Express routing - the framework has its own tests)
- Getter/setter methods with no logic
- CSS/styling (use visual regression tools if needed, not unit tests)
- Third-party library behavior (test YOUR usage of it, not the library itself). Exception: contract/smoke tests around critical integrations (third-party SDKs, external APIs) are valuable.
- Private methods directly (test through the public API). Exception: complex internal algorithms may warrant direct tests when the public surface is too coarse.

