## Test Structure (AAA Pattern)

Every test follows **Arrange -> Act -> Assert**:

```
it("should return 403 when user lacks permission", async () => {
  // Arrange: set up preconditions
  const regularUser = createTestUser({ role: "viewer" });
  const targetResource = createTestResource();

  // Act: perform the action
  const response = await request(app)
    .delete(`/api/resources/${targetResource.id}`)
    .set("Authorization", `Bearer ${regularUser.token}`);

  // Assert: verify the result
  expect(response.status).toBe(403);
  expect(response.body.error).toBe("You do not have permission to perform this action.");
});
```

**Rules:**
- Prefer focused assertions - multiple asserts on the same result are fine (e.g., check status AND body). Avoid testing unrelated behaviors in one test.
- Arrange section should be minimal - use factories/fixtures for complex setup
- Act section should be ONE function call or ONE request
- Minimize logic in tests - avoid complex conditionals. Table-driven tests and parameterized loops are fine for testing variations of the same behavior.

