## Common Patterns

### Testing API Endpoints

```
describe("Resource collection API - create") {
  it("should create resource when authorized")
  it("should return 401 when not authenticated")
  it("should return 403 when not authorized")
  it("should return 400 when required fields missing")
  it("should return 400 when field format invalid")
  it("should return 409 when unique constraint violated")
}
```

### Testing Auth Flows (IF your project has authentication)

```
describe("Authentication") {
  it("should authenticate with valid credentials")
  it("should reject invalid credential secret")
  it("should reject unknown user with same error as invalid secret")
  it("should rate limit after repeated failures")
  it("should issue valid signed token on successful auth")
  it("should reject expired token")
  it("should end session and invalidate credentials on logout")
}
```

### Testing Permissions

```
describe("Permission checks") {
  it("should allow admin to access all resources")
  it("should restrict user to own data")
  it("should allow scoped role to see filtered data")
  it("should return 403 for cross-scope access")
}
```

---

## Tools

**The principle:** Use the standard, most-adopted testing framework for your stack. If your language has a built-in test runner, prefer it. For E2E, use whatever the community has converged on for your platform (browser-based for web, native test frameworks for mobile).

**Rules:**
- Pick ONE unit/integration framework per project - don't mix
- Pick ONE E2E framework per project - don't mix
- Prefer frameworks with active maintenance and community adoption
- If your stack has a built-in test runner (Go, Dart, Swift), use it over third-party alternatives
